## 4. Development Workflow

### 4.1 Phase Gate (Iron Rule)

> **Lower layers must be complete, stable, fully tested before building upper layers.**

- "Complete": all features listed in phase roadmap implemented, no TODO/stub/placeholder
- "Stable": all tests pass, both build paths zero errors, no known regression
- "Fully tested": positive + boundary + error path tests, coverage meets roadmap target
- If current phase needs missing prerequisite, fix the lower phase first — never hack around it
- **Cooldown periods** (mandatory no-new-features): #1 Week 33-35, #2 Week 55-57, #3 Week 83-85

### 4.2 Phase Execution Protocol

```
Plan -> Implement -> Test -> Demo (optional) -> Verify -> Gate Check
```

| Step | Requirement |
|------|-------------|
| **Plan** | Create TODO list (`todo_list` tool), each sub-step has clear acceptance criteria |
| **Implement** | One sub-step at a time. Follow coding standards below. |
| **Test** | Tests written alongside implementation. `TEST(ModuleName, SpecificBehavior)`. Zero regression. **Mandatory test categories per component** (see §4.4). |
| **Demo** | Milestone phases provide interactive demo (GLFW window), in `demos/<name>/` |
| **Verify** | Both build paths (default + vulkan) must pass with zero errors and zero failures |
| **Gate Check** | All features complete, tests sufficient, no residual issues. Only then proceed. |

### 4.2.1 Phase Planning Quality Checklist (Mandatory)

Before marking a phase plan as "PLANNING COMPLETE", agent must verify the following checklist. These checks prevent the class of planning omissions where steady-state behavior is specified but transition/boundary/interaction behavior is not.

| # | Check | What to do | Example failure mode |
|---|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| 1 | **Interaction Scenario Walkthrough** | For every user-facing subsystem, mentally simulate the 3-5 most common real-time interaction sequences (zoom, pan, resize, drag, undo). Write down what happens at each continuous state transition. | MSDF/bitmap hard-switch pop during scroll-zoom |
| 2 | **Algorithm Parameter Extreme Analysis** | For every core algorithm, identify its key parameter and analyze behavior at min/max/zero/negative extremes. Document degenerate cases and their mitigations. | `screenPxRange -> 0` producing noise; atlas page count -> 0; empty glyph run |
| 3 | **Subsystem Seam Behavior** | When two tasks share a boundary (one produces, other consumes, or they operate on overlapping parameter ranges), explicitly define the behavior at the seam. "What happens at the exact switchover point?" must have a written answer. | MSDF task and Bitmap task both claim 8px but neither defines the crossfade |
| 4 | **Dynamic Quality Metrics** | In addition to throughput/latency targets, define at least one visual-continuity metric per user-facing subsystem: "no visible pop", "smooth fade", "no flicker during X". | Missing "continuous zoom shows no pop" acceptance criterion |
| 5 | **Known-Defect Survey** | When adopting a technique (MSDF, SDF, LOD, etc.), search for its known limitations and community-reported artifacts. Cross-check that mitigations are planned. | MSDF zoom-out artifacts widely reported in three.js/Godot forums but not addressed |

